Computing gene activity scores from Peak2Gene Links

The following function is based on the function used in Cicero to compute gene activity scores from co-accessibility scores of sites linked to each gene k. For more information on how the calculation is implemented in Cicero see here: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1097276518305471?via%3Dihub#sec4

Implementation for peak-to-gene linkage matrix

The main idea is to adapt the function which is used to determine gene activity scores based on co-accessibility scores (scATAC-seq data only, no scRNA-seq data) to our case. For our case we want it to work for peak-to-gene links. Here we do not want to differentiate between proximal and distal sites of a gene, but simply use all peaks which are correlated with our gene k.

To create peak-to-gene links, cell aggregates were created and the peak regions were correlated with the gene regions across all cells.

Below you can see the peak-to-gene linkage dataframe.

p2g <- getPeak2GeneLinks(
  ArchRProj = proj,
  corCutOff = -1,
  resolution = 1,
  FDRCutOff = 1e-04,
  varCutOffATAC = .25,
  varCutOffRNA = .25, 
  returnLoops = FALSE
)

First, we will create a sparse matrix for the peak2gene links from the dataframe shown above.

This is our correlation matrix \(U \in{\mathbb{R}^{KxJ}}\) with \(K\) being the total number of genes and \(J\) being the total number of peaks. Each entry \(U_{kj}\) corresponds to the correlation value between peak \(j\) and gene \(k\) across all cell aggregates.

# create a sparse matrix with the correlation values
p2g_mat <- sparseMatrix(i = p2g$RowIndex, 
                        j = p2g$ColIndex,
                        x = p2g$Correlation,
                        dims = c(length(unique(p2g$idxRNA)),
                                 length(unique(p2g$idxATAC))),
                        dimnames = list(unique(p2g$idxRNA), 
                                        unique(p2g$idxATAC)))

print(paste0("The sparse matrix of correlations has dimensions: ", dim(p2g_mat)[[1]], " genes and ", dim(p2g_mat)[[2]], " peaks."))
## [1] "The sparse matrix of correlations has dimensions: 16418 genes and 260052 peaks."

Now we will calculate a weighted sum of accessible peaks in a cell. The weights are the corresponding correlation values between a particular peak \(j\) and gene \(k\). \(A\in\mathbb{R}^{JxI}\) is the binary peak accessibility matrix with \(A_{ji} = 1\) if peak \(j\) is found in cell \(i\) and \(A_{ji} = 0\) otherwise.

\(R_{ki} = \sum_{U_{kj}A_{ji}}\), where \(R_{ki}\) corresponds to the gene activity score of gene \(k\) in cell \(i\).

\(R = U I\) with \(R \in \mathbb{R}^{KxI}\).

Below you can see the first few entries of this gene activity score matrix. Note that some entries are negative.

# we subset the accessibility matrix to contain only peaks which are also 
# included in our p2g matrix
peak_mat_subset <- peak_mat[as.integer(colnames(p2g_mat)), ]

# Now we can compute a weighted sum of peak2gene correlations for each
# peak and gene

Linear regression to account for differences in library size.

The aggregate correlation values will depend on scATAC-seq library depth in each cell. We can capture this relationship with a linear regression.

\(\log{\sum_{k}{r_k} = \beta_0 + \beta_A \log(\sum_j{A_{ji}})}\)

# lets create a copy of the matrix
scores <- corr_sum

# create a dataframe for computing the linear model
normalization_df <- data.frame(cell = colnames(scores),
                               total_activity = colSums(scores),
                               total_sites = colSums(peak_mat_subset))

#plot the relationship between library depth and activity scores
normalization_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = total_sites, y = total_activity)) + geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Relationship between activity scores and library depth", 
       y = "total activity", x = "peaks")



# compute a linear model
activity_model <- stats::lm(log(total_activity) ~ log(total_sites), 
                            data = normalization_df)

# extract the fitted model
normalization_df$fitted_curve <- exp(as.vector(predict(activity_model, type = "response")))

# plot the fitted model
normalization_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = total_sites, y = fitted_curve)) + geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Fitted Model capturing relationship between activity scores and library depth", y = "Fitted curve - activity scores", x = "number of peaks") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(normalization_df$fitted_curve), color = "orange")


print(paste0("Mean fitted activity: ", mean(normalization_df$fitted_curve)))
## [1] "Mean fitted activity: 3768.75967739201"

SizeFactors

The output of the linear model is used to scale the accessibility we computed above.

\(\tilde{R}_{ki}= R_{ki} * \frac{\sum_{i}{r_i}}{r_i}\)

If an activity score \(R_{ki}\) for a given cell \(i\) is smaller than the average activity score, the size factor will be >1 and if the activity score is bigger than the average activity score the size factor will be <1. After correcting with the size factors we would expect the linear increase in activity with increasing number of accessibile sites to be corrected for.

In the plot below we can see that we have corrected for this linear relationship.

# each cell is scaled by a factor corresponding to its library depth
#size_factors <- log(normalization_df$fitted_curve) / mean(log(normalization_df$fitted_curve))
#size_factors <- log(sum(normalization_df$fitted_curve)) / log(normalization_df$fitted_curve) 

size_factors <- mean(normalization_df$fitted_curve) / normalization_df$fitted_curve


ggplot(as.data.frame(size_factors), aes(x = size_factors)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1, color="orange", alpha=0.8)

Transform

Then we exponentiate the values, because the RNA-seq measures are typically log-normally distributed. To create relative exponentiated gene accessibility values, we scale them by the total exponentiated gene accesibility values. We get our gene activity scores \(G_{ki}\).

Because for log transformation of gene expression counts we add a pseudocount, we need to subtract one here:

\(e^{\tilde{R}} - 1\)

\(G_{ki} = \frac{e^{\tilde{R}_{ki}}-1}{\sum_k{e^{\tilde{R}_{ki}}-1}}\)

Below you can see the first few entries of the exponentiated values, before scaling.

# plot the total sites vs total activities after correction
